PHASE 2  │  Textbook Ingestion & RAG Pipeline
Weeks 4–6     ·   PDF → chunks → embeddings → Pinecone → semantic search

Goal
Build the knowledge backbone. Every AI answer in this system must trace back to the student's own textbook. The quality of this pipeline directly determines the quality of every teaching session, every test, and every explanation.

Optimized RAG Architecture
Stage
Optimized Implementation
Stage 1 — Upload
Student uploads PDF via presigned Supabase Storage URL. Backend receives callback, updates textbooks.status = 'indexing', fires Celery task.
Stage 2 — Extract
PyMuPDF extracts text per page. CRITICAL: detect and skip image-only pages (scanned textbooks). Use pytesseract OCR fallback for scanned pages — original roadmap silently produces empty chunks.
Stage 3 — Chunk
800-token chunks, 100-token overlap. IMPROVEMENT: add chapter boundary detection using heading regex. Chunks never cross chapter boundaries — prevents context pollution between topics.
Stage 4 — Embed
OpenAI text-embedding-3-small for each chunk. Batch in groups of 100 to stay under API rate limits. Cache embeddings in Redis for 24h — re-indexing the same book is instant.
Stage 5 — Store
Upsert to Pinecone with namespace = f'{student_id}_{subject}'. Metadata: chapter, page, subject, grade. FAISS in dev only.
Stage 6 — Query
Query → embed → Pinecone similarity search (top 5) → MMR re-rank (reduces duplicate chunks) → inject into LLM context.

Critical Code — OCR Fallback for Scanned Books

🔑  CRITICAL: Many Indian textbooks (especially state board) are scanned PDFs. Without OCR fallback, these produce zero chunks and the AI tutor has nothing to teach from. This is the single biggest gap in the original roadmap.

import fitz, pytesseract
from PIL import Image
import io
 
def extract_text_smart(pdf_path: str) -> list[dict]:
    doc = fitz.open(pdf_path)
    pages = []
    for i, page in enumerate(doc):
        text = page.get_text('text').strip()
        if len(text) < 50:  # likely scanned
            # render page as image → OCR
            pix = page.get_pixmap(dpi=300)
            img = Image.open(io.BytesIO(pix.tobytes('png')))
            text = pytesseract.image_to_string(img, lang='eng+hin')
        pages.append({'text': text, 'page': i+1, 'ocr': len(text)<50})
    return pages
 
# Chapter detection — headings in CBSE books are usually
# ALL CAPS lines fewer than 60 chars
import re
def detect_chapter(text: str) -> str | None:
    match = re.search(r'^([A-Z][A-Z\s]{4,50})$', text, re.MULTILINE)
    return match.group(1).strip() if match else None

Pinecone Setup (Production)
from pinecone import Pinecone, ServerlessSpec
from langchain_pinecone import PineconeVectorStore
from langchain_openai import OpenAIEmbeddings
 
pc = Pinecone(api_key=PINECONE_API_KEY)
 
# Create index once (idempotent)
if 'aitutor' not in [i.name for i in pc.list_indexes()]:
    pc.create_index('aitutor', dimension=1536,
        spec=ServerlessSpec(cloud='aws', region='us-east-1'))
 
def get_vectorstore(student_id: str, subject: str):
    embeddings = OpenAIEmbeddings(model='text-embedding-3-small')
    return PineconeVectorStore(
        index_name='aitutor',
        embedding=embeddings,
        namespace=f'{student_id}_{subject}'
    )
 
def retrieve_context(question: str, student_id: str,
                     subject: str, k: int = 5) -> str:
    vs = get_vectorstore(student_id, subject)
    # MMR = Maximal Marginal Relevance — reduces duplicate chunks
    docs = vs.max_marginal_relevance_search(question, k=k, fetch_k=20)
    return '\n\n---\n\n'.join(d.page_content for d in docs)

