Voice Pipeline — VAD Streaming (Key Improvement)
The original roadmap sends full audio blobs after the student stops speaking. This causes 2–4 second transcription delays. Replace with Voice Activity Detection (VAD) streaming using @ricky0123/vad-web in the browser:

// frontend/lib/voiceSession.ts
import { useMicVAD } from '@ricky0123/vad-react'
 
export function useVoiceSession(sessionId: string) {
  const { start, stop } = useMicVAD({
    onSpeechStart: () => console.log('Listening...'),
    onSpeechEnd: async (audio: Float32Array) => {
      // VAD fires immediately when student stops speaking
      // audio = Float32Array WAV — no silence padding
      const blob = encodeWAV(audio)
      const text = await transcribe(blob)    // POST /voice/transcribe
      ws.send(JSON.stringify({ type: 'student_text', text }))
    },
    positiveSpeechThreshold: 0.8,
    minSpeechFrames: 3,
  })
  return { start, stop }
}
 
// Result: transcription starts 0ms after student stops speaking
// vs original: 1-2s of silence wait + upload delay

WebSocket Session Architecture
Concern
Solution
Connection
Student opens ws://api/ws/session/{id}. Session engine loaded from Redis. Greeting streamed immediately.
Token stream
Each LLM token streamed as { type:'chunk', text } — student sees response appear word by word.
Turn end
{ type:'turn_end' } signals frontend to play TTS audio. TTS request fires in parallel with LLM streaming.
Reconnection
If WebSocket drops, client auto-reconnects with same session_id. Redis state preserves full history.
Heartbeat
30-second ping/pong. If 2 consecutive pongs missed, server saves transcript and closes session gracefully.
Concurrency
Each session runs in an asyncio task. FastAPI handles 500+ concurrent sessions on a single worker.

